related_questions.question: What is the wonton wrapper made of?
related_questions.snippet: Traditional Chinese wonton wrappers are made from wheat flour, eggs and water, and can be used to wrap around any number of fillings to be cooked in soups or fried.

related_questions.question: What is a good substitute for wonton wrappers?
related_questions.snippet: In a pinch, egg roll wrappers can be used for wontons. Keep in mind they are larger and thicker than wonton wrappers, so your final result may be different.
related_questions.title: egg roll wrappers

related_questions.question: Are spring roll wrappers the same as wonton wrappers?
related_questions.snippet: Wonton and egg roll wrappers are made with a similar wheat and egg dough. However, wonton wrappers are smaller in size compared to the other two. Spring roll wrappers do not contain eggs and are thinner than wonton or egg roll wrappers. Wonton/Shumai wrappers imported from Japan are smaller in size.

related_questions.question: Are wonton wrappers just rice paper?
related_questions.snippet: Both are staples in Asian cooking. Rice paper is just what it sounds like — thin, stiff sheets made primarily from rice, though tapioca starch can be mixed in. The most common size is an 8-inch round. Wonton wrappers are also thin, but the primary ingredient in the dough is wheat.
